    <!-- When creating a new activity, make a copy of this file with appropriate name -->
    <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25in" xml:id="ws-volslice">
      <title>Worksheet for Section 7.2</title>

      <objectives>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find the volume of a solid by slicing.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find the volume of a solid of revolution using the disc or washer
              method.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </objectives>


      <page>
        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p> The base of a solid object <m>S</m> is the region bounded by <m>y = \sqrt{x}</m> and <m>y
              = 0</m> for <m>x \leq 1</m>. Cross-sections for the object perpendicular to the <m>x</m>-axis
              are squares. What is the volume of <m>S</m>? </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>
            <p> A slice through the solid perpendicular to the <m>x</m>-axis at <m>x</m> has volume <me>\Delta
              V \approx \left(\sqrt{x}\right)^2 \,\Delta x = x \,\Delta x</me> So <me>V = \int_0^1
              x\,dx = \frac{1}{2}</me>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p> The base of a solid object <m>S</m> is the region bounded by the parabola <m>y^2 =
                3x</m> and the line <m>x = 3</m>. Cross-sections for the object perpendicular to the <m>
              y</m>-axis are equilateral triangles. What is the volume of <m>S</m>? </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>
            <p> First, recall that the area of an equilateral triangle of side length <m>s</m> is <m>
              \frac{s^2\sqrt{3}}{4}</m>. A slice of the solid perpendicular to the <m>y</m> axis at <m>
              y</m> is an equilateral triangle with side length <m>3 - y^2/3</m>. So <me>\Delta V
              \approx \left(3 - \frac{y^2}{3}\right)^2 \frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}\,\Delta x</me> The volume
              is an integral form of this, to be sure. What are the limits? The curves intersect
              when <m>y^2 = 9 \implies y = \pm 3</m>. So <me>V = \int_{-3}^3 \left(3 -
              \frac{y^2}{3}\right)^2 \frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}\,dy = \frac{36 \sqrt{3}}{5} \approx 12.4708.</me>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p> Find the volume obtained by rotating the region bounded by <m>y = \sqrt{x}</m> and <m>y
              = 0</m> for <m>x \leq 1</m> about the <m>x</m>-axis. </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>
            <p>
              <me>V = \int_0^1 \pi \left(\sqrt{x}\right)^2 \,dx = \pi \int_0^1 x\,dx = \frac{\pi}{2}</me>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p> Find the volume obtained by rotating the region bounded by <m>y = \sqrt{x}</m> and <m>y
              = x^2</m> about the <m>x</m>-axis. </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p> The volume is <me>V =\pi \int_0^1 \left(\sqrt{x} - x^2\right)^2 \,dx=
                \frac{3\pi}{10}</me>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p> Find the volume obtained by rotating the region bounded by <m>y = \sqrt{x}</m> and <m>y
              = x^2</m> about the about the line <m>y = -1</m>. </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p> The inner and outer radii of the slice at <m>x</m> are not <m>\sqrt{x}</m> and <m>
              x^2</m>, but <m>\sqrt{x} + 1</m> and <m>x^2 + 1</m>. So <me>V = \int_0^1 \pi
              \left(\left(\sqrt{x} + 1\right)^2 - \left(x^2 + 1\right)^2 \right) \,dx =
              \frac{29\pi}{30}</me>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p> Let <m>R</m> be the region bounded by <m>y=x</m>, <m>y=-x</m>, and <m>x=1</m>.
              Compute the volume of the solid formed by revolving <m>R</m> around (a) the <m>y</m>-axis
              and (b) the line <m>x=-1</m>. </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p> We slice the solid perpendicular to the <m>y</m>-axis. At level <m>y</m> the slices
              are washers with outer radius <m>1</m> and inner radius <m>x= |y|</m>. So <me>\begin{aligned}
              V = \int_{-1}^1 \pi \left(1^2 - |y|^2\right) &amp;= 2\pi \int_{0}^1 \left(1 -
              y^2\right) = 2 \pi \cdot \frac{2}{3} = \frac{4\pi}{3}
                \end{aligned}</me>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="1in">
          <statement>
            <p> Find the volume of a sphere of radius <m>r</m> by rotating <m>y = \sqrt{r^2 - x^2}</m>
              about the <m>x</m>-axis. </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p> Slice the sphere perpendicular to the <m>x</m>-axis. The slice at level <m>x</m> has
              area <m>\pi\left(\sqrt{r^2-x^2}\right) = \pi (r^2 -x^2)</m>. So <me>\begin{aligned}
                V &amp;= \int_{-r}^r \pi (r^2 -x^2)\,dx = 2\pi \int_0^r (r^2 - x^2)\,dx \\
                &amp;= 2\pi \left[r^2x - \frac{x^3}{3}\right]^r_0 = 2\pi \left[r^3 -
              \frac{r^3}{3}\right] \\
                &amp;= 2\pi \left(\frac{2r^3}{3}\right) = \frac{4}{3}{\pi r^3}\\
                \end{aligned}</me>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

      </page>
    </worksheet>
